Results
      A total of 62,370 post-menopausal women from 26 studies (27,585 cases and 34,785 controls), were included in the analyses (Table S1). Cases were slightly older (mean age: 64 years) than controls (mean age: 63 years). Current use of MHT was more common among breast cancer cases (34%) than controls (28%), showing a suggestive increased breast cancer risk (OR = 1.16; 95% CI: 0.99, 1.36; Fig. 1A). A total of 20,131 cases and 22,601 controls from 18 studies also had information on current use of EPT. Current EPT use was more common among cases (19%) than controls (13%) and was associated with an estimated 48% risk increase of breast cancer, compared to non-EPT users (OR: 1.48; 95% CI: 1.29, 1.70; Fig. 1B).Figure 1Main effects of current menopausal hormone therapy use and breast cancer risk by study. (A) Current use of any menopausal hormone therapy. (B) Current use of combined estrogen–progesterone menopausal hormone therapy.
